metadata.name: Stepping Stones #527
metadata.description:
"Stepping Stones" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Performance in Code: Deciphering Value in Generative Art, Art Basel Miami Beach, 2022

Stepping Stones explores the idea that the whole is greater than the sum of its parts. Simple patterns, shapes, textures, and colors are arranged in randomly selected ways. Overlaying shapes distort and blend, breaking these objects apart and causing complex forms to emerge. Combining these individual features together results in varying outcomes, from surprisingly simple to wildly chaotic.

---------------

Controls:
Press 1-6 to change the scale of the canvas (1 = default, 2500px x 2500px, 6 = 15,000px x 15,000px)
S (or double tap on mobile): Save output at current size
C: Toggle cutout shapes visibility
H: Toggle cutout outlines visibility
B: Iterate border sizes (none, default, 1.5x, 2x, 3x)
T: Toggle texture visibility
F: Toggle fullscreen
Add the url params x and y to set custom dimensions. For example, add &x=1500&y=500 for a 1500px x 500px image

---------------

Tyler Boswell (@teaboswell) 2022

metadata.name: a fortiori #281
metadata.description:
Energy is everywhere: it’s moving our bodies, buzzing around a city, growing the universe, and connecting everything within it. Perhaps the strongest symbol humans use for energy – for ideas, life, and the various incarnations of power – is light itself. 

For centuries, each form of art has tried to capture the energetic luminescence of a bright light, a warm glow, a spark... if we could only draw with its pure brilliance! From Caravaggio’s diagonal beams, to Picasso drawing with light across Gjon Mili’s photographic emulsions… this pursuit persists through obsessive efforts by artists of every media. 

a fortiori seeks to capture this power of light with code, output on the native illumination of modern screens. The visual deconstruction of light and its reassembly into a frozen moment produces the tangible shards of each spark – resulting in a sum of marks that exceeds the value of their individual parts. It’s then the obsessive energy of generative art’s looping and controlled randomness that enable its repeated mark making, of all types, to express the nearly-intangible intensity of light.

What one hand might communicate in drawing, with light or stick or keyboard, 100 hands would therefore say 100 times louder, clearer, and more impactfully. And if one could capture the authentic energy of traveling light in a single image, it stands to reason that 500 of these images will multiply their energy-inducing qualities together, and exponentially grow their collective power. In this idea, the medium is the message – proving the power of the medium, and its ability to generate energy.


--------

TENDER x Thomas Noya
December 2022

Source code is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License as published by the Free Software Foundation.

a fortiori was created in p5.js and is optimized for live output in Chrome. Press these keys in live view to control the art and render high resolution versions of any token:

x = pause
y = play
1 = 1000x1000
2-9 = 2000x2000, …, 9000x9000
0 = 10000x10000
t = 12500x12500
f = 15000x15000
s = save PNG

Outputs beyond 10,000 pixels square are dependent on individual computer and browser capabilities. 

10% of all primary and secondary proceeds donated directly to Girls Who Code

◉_◉

metadata.name: Tangentum #81
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: A Lullaby for Euclid #5
metadata.description:
Geometric figures move in pendulous loops as they swirl through the scribbling winds of infinite (pseudo) randomly generated numbers.

The plot is simple, but the story lasts forever.

Controls
Press [p] to pause/unpause, or tap the image on a mobile device
Press [r] to restart the animation
Press [s] to save a copy of the current frame
Add “?pd=4” to the URL to reload at a higher pixel density

metadata.name: Endeavor #25
metadata.description:
Endeavor is a generative system structured to create abstract mountains.

When I look at the outputs, I am reminded of the things I would like to achieve. I would be curious to know what comes to your mind when you ask yourself, "What is my goal? What do I intend to do?"

Controls:

'p' - Play an animation that draws the mountain layer by layer
'1' - Default, textured image
'2' - No border
'3' - Flat, non-textured image
'4' - Flat with no border

Each of the 128 editions chooses one of five forms, all of which explore variety in layout, shading, and color composition.

25% of the royalties for each edition will pass to the original minter.

Each output is generated from code written in p5js.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

objkt.name: Ode to Bugs and Happy Accidents #191

metadata.name: Ode to Bugs and Happy Accidents #191
metadata.description:
“If debugging is the process of removing software bugs, then programming must be the process of putting them in.”

― Edsger W. Dijkstra


This artwork is dedicated to happy accidents, mistakes, and bugs. Every key part of it is based on some sort of failure: wrong variable value, unstopped recursion, untimely function call. And sometimes it leads to pleasant results.

It was created to celebrate #fxhashturnsone event.

The earnings are partly donated to:
- Processing Foundation
- #TezosStandsWithUkraine

[a] - toggle animation
[1] - save PNG in low resolution
[2] - save PNG in medium resolution
[3] - save PNG in high resolution
[4] - save PNG in ultra-high resolution

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js

By Collapsar Beauty
CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: n Forms #118
metadata.description:
Hand-scrawled documentation of abstract structures. A journal from another realm.

Press 's' to save an image while in full-screen mode.

If you want to increase the resolution of the saved image, add e.g. &size=2000 after the live/fullscreen view URL to render the canvas at that specific pixel width (default = browser sized). This will be dependent on your system specifications, but outputs of up to 8000px wide, or above, should be possible.

Usually loads best in Chrome

metadata.name: View #112
metadata.description:
Generative art is rarely representational, this work seeks to explore what can be achieved by an algorithm with the medium of pixel art. 

The algorithm generates a 200x200 pixel art image showing a view from a window over the sea. There are three backdrops available, all completely procedural. No baked-in sprites were used. I hope that the love that went into making it is clear.


Please enjoy the view.

metadata.name: sun peel stare #12
metadata.description:
have you seen the sky today? (how often do you look?)

will it find you fractured or aligned? (or will it not see you at all?)

what don’t we see when the light is in our eyes? (do we even want to?)

[ in “live view” you can press: ]
[ P : process more/pause ]
[ S or 1 : save 3000x3000 png ]
[ 2 :  save 6000x6000 png ]
[ 3 :  save 12000x12000 png ]

(after initial render, you can save at any point of processing.)

Nowhere but here, before—a prequel, of sorts,
with nothing yet built to fall;
a jagged canvas,
unowned, unknown…
brutal even if naive
